This paper primarily focuses on the security and privacy aspects of in-browser cryptojacking, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The paper also involves analyzing the economic feasibility of cryptojacking as an alternative to online advertisement, which could be categorized under software engineering (cs.SE) and social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper also involves analyzing the impact of cryptojacking on system resources, which could be categorized under distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). Finally, the paper discusses countermeasures against cryptojacking, which could be categorized under cryptography and security (cs.CY).
